"Gallo K.P., Adegoke J.O., Owen T.W., Elvidge C.D.","Satellite-based detection of global urban heat-island temperature influence",2002,"Journal of Geophysical Research Atmospheres","107","24",,"XXXXI","XXXXII",,,10.1029/2002JD002588,"http://www.scopus.com/inward/record.url?eid=2-s2.0-1942461481&partnerID=40&md5=19184a59d615d3e07d55d91d20ccbc08","NOAA, National Environmental Satellite, Data, and Information Service, Office of Research and Applications, Camp Springs, MD, United States; CIRA, Colorado State University, Fort Collins, CO, United States; NOAA, National Climatic Data Center, Asheville, NC, United States; NOAA, National Geophysical Data Center, Boulder, CO, United States; USGS, EROS, Data Center, Sioux Falls, SD, United States; Department of Geosciences, University of Missouri-Kansas City, Kansas City, MO 64110, United States; NOAA, National Geophysical Data Center, 325 Broadway, Boulder, CO 80303, United States; USGS, EROS, Data Center, 47914 252nd Street, Sioux Falls, SD 57198, United States; NOAA, National Climatic Data Center, 151 Patton Avenue, Asheville, NC 28801, United States","Gallo, K.P., NOAA, National Environmental Satellite, Data, and Information Service, Office of Research and Applications, Camp Springs, MD, United States, USGS, EROS, Data Center, Sioux Falls, SD, United States, USGS, EROS, Data Center, 47914 252nd Street, Sioux Falls, SD 57198, United States; Adegoke, J.O., CIRA, Colorado State University, Fort Collins, CO, United States, Department of Geosciences, University of Missouri-Kansas City, Kansas City, MO 64110, United States; Owen, T.W., NOAA, National Climatic Data Center, Asheville, NC, United States, NOAA, National Climatic Data Center, 151 Patton Avenue, Asheville, NC 28801, United States; Elvidge, C.D., NOAA, National Geophysical Data Center, Boulder, CO, United States, NOAA, National Geophysical Data Center, 325 Broadway, Boulder, CO 80303, United States","This study utilizes a satellite-based methodology to assess the urban heat-island influence during warm season months for over 4400 stations included in the Global Historical Climatology Network of climate stations. The methodology includes local and regional satellite retrievals of an indicator of the presence green photosynthetically active vegetation at and around the stations. The difference in local and regional samples of the normalized difference vegetation index (NDVI) is used to estimate differences in mean air temperature. Stations classified as urban averaged 0.90°C (N. Hemisphere) and 0.92°C (S. Hemisphere) warmer than the surrounding environment on the basis of the NDVI-derived temperature estimates. Additionally, stations classified as rural averaged 0.19°C (N. Hemisphere) and 0.16°C (S. Hemisphere) warmer than the surrounding environment. The NDVI-derived temperature estimates were found to be in reasonable agreement with temperature differences observed between climate stations. The results suggest that satellite-derived data sets can be used to estimate the urban heat-island temperature influence on a global basis and that a more detailed analysis of rural stations and their surrounding environment may be necessary to assure that temperature trends derived from assumed rural environments are not influenced by changes in land use/land cover. Copyright 2002 by the American Geophysical Union.","1630 Global Change: Impact phenomena; 3309 Meteorology and Atmospheric Dynamics: Climatology (1620); 3322 Meteorology and Atmospheric Dynamics: Land/atmosphere interactions; 3360 Meteorology and Atmospheric Dynamics: Remote sensing; Urban heat-island",,,,,,,"Balling Jr., R.C., Idso, C.D., Analysis of adjustments to the United States Historical Climatology Network (USHCN) temperature database (2002) Geophys. Res. Lett., 29, p. 1387. , doi:10.1029/2002GL014825; Belward, A.S., Estes, J.E., Kline, K.D., The IGBP-DIS global 1-km land-cover dataset DISCover: A project overview (1999) Photogramm. Eng. Remote Sens., 65, pp. 1013-1020; Changnon, S.A., Inadvertent weather modification in urban areas: Lessons for global climate change (1992) Bull. Am. Meteorol. Soc., 73, pp. 619-627; Christy, J.R., When was the hottest summer? (2002) Bull. Am. Meteorol. Soc., 83, pp. 723-734; Danko, D.M., The digital chart of the world project (1992) Photogramm. Eng. Remote Sens., 58, pp. 1125-1128; Easterling, D.R., Maximum and minimum temperature trends for the globe (1997) Science, 277, pp. 364-367; Eidenshink, J.C., Faundeen, J.L., The 1 km AVHRR global land data set: First stages in implementation (1994) Int. J. Remote Sens., 15, pp. 3443-3462; Elvidge, C.D., Imhoff, M.L., Baugh, K.E., Hobson, V.R., Nelson, I., Safran, J., Dietz, J.B., Tuttle, B.T., Night-time lights of the world: 1994-1995 (2001) ISPRS J. Photogramm. Remote Sens., 56, pp. 81-99; Gallo, K.P., Owen, T.W., Satellite-based adjustments for the urban heat-island temperature bias (1999) J. Appl. Meteorol., 38, pp. 806-813; Gallo, K.P., Owen, T.W., A sampling strategy for satellite sensor-based assessments of the urban heat-island bias (2002) Int. J. Remote Sens., 23, pp. 1935-1939; Gallo, K.P., McNab, A.L., Karl, T.R., Brown, J.F., Hood, J.J., Tarpley, J.D., The Use of NOAA AVHRR data for assessment of the urban heat-island effect (1993) J. Appl. Meteorol., 32, pp. 899-908; Gallo, K.P., Easterling, D.R., Peterson, T.C., The influence of land use/ land cover on climatological values of the diurnal temperature range (1996) J. Lim., 9, pp. 2941-2944; Gallo, K.P., Owen, T.W., Easterling, D.R., Jamason, P.F., Temperature trends of the U.S. Historical Climatology Network based on satellite-designated land use/land cover (1999) J. Clim., 19, pp. 1344-1348; Hansen, J., Ruedy, R., Sato, M., Imhoff, M., Lawrence, W., Easterling, D., Peterson, T., Karl, T., A closer look at United States and global surface temperature change (2001) J. Geophys. Res., 106, pp. 23,947-23,963; Jones, P.D., Hemispheric surface temperature variations: A reanalysis and an update to 1993 (1994) J. Cim., 7, pp. 1794-1802; Jones, P.D., Raper, S.C.B., Bradley, R.S., Diaz, H.F., Kelly, P.M., Wigley, T.M.L., Northern Hemispheric surface air temperature variations: 1851-1984 (1986) J. Clim. Appl. Meteorol., 25, pp. 161-179; Jones, P.D., Raper, S.C.B., Wigley, T.M.L., Southern Hemispheric surface air temperature variations: 1851-1984 (1986) J. Clim. Appl. Meteorol., 25, pp. 1213-1230; Karl, T.R., Diaz, H.F., Kukla, G., Urbanization: Its detection and effect in the United States climate record (1988) J. Clim., 1, pp. 1099-1123; Karl, T.R., A new perspective on recent global warming: Asymmetic trends of daily maximum and minimum temperature (1993) Bull. Am. Meteorol. Soc., 74, pp. 1007-1024; Kukla, G., Gavin, J., Karl, T.R., Urban warming (1986) J. Clim. Appl. Meteorol., 25, pp. 1265-1270; Landsberg, H.E., (1981) The Urban Climate, , Academic, New York; Lougeay, R., Brazel, A., Hubble, M., Monitoring intraurban temperature patterns and associated land cover in Phoenix, Arizona using Landsat thermal data (1996) Geocarto Int., 11, pp. 79-90; Oke, T.R., City size and the urban heat-island (1973) Atmos. Environ., 7, pp. 769-779; Owen, T.W., Gallo, K.P., Updated population metadata for United States Historical Climatology Network stations (2000) J. Clim., 13, pp. 4028-4033; Owen, T.W., Gallo, K.P., Elvidge, C.D., Baugh, K.E., Using DMSP-OLS light frequency data to categorize urban environments associated with U. S. climate observing stations (1998) Int. J. Remote Sens, 19, pp. 3451-3456; Peterson, T.C., Gallo, K.P., Lawrimore, J., Owen, T.W., Huang, A., McKittrick, D.A., Global rural temperature trends (1999) Geophys. Res. Lett., 26, pp. 329-332","Gallo, K.P.; NOAA, National Environmental Satellite, Data, and Information Service, Office of Research and Applications, Camp Springs, MD, United States; email: kgallo@usgs.gov",,,"Blackwell Publishing Ltd",,,,,01480227,,,,"English","J. Geophys. Res. D Atmos.",Article,Scopus,2-s2.0-1942461481
